/*
 ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
 │                                  CSS for SPECIFIC DATES                                     │
 └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
		If you are generating this CSS programatically and wish to generate a class for a
		specific date, then name your class in this format: .date-YYYY-MM-DD

		For example, if you were going to have special CSS for June 19th, 2025
		then you would name your class

		.date-2025-06-19 {}

		NOTE: the month and day MUST be 2 digits. The year MUST be 4 digits.

		Here is an easy snippet to generate the class name:

	my $classname_to_print_to_css_file = 'date-' . sprintf("%04d%02d%02d", $YEAR, $MONTH, $DAY);
	
		You could modify the CSS delivery script (calendar_css.pl) to automatically generate
		and insert the date classes.

 ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
 │                                  CSS for AGENDA FORMAT                                      │
 └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Here’s a concise UL vs LI CSS cheat sheet for reference:

Property / Style        UL (container)  LI (item)	Notes
list-style-type         Yes              No         Defines bullets/numbers for the list, not per item.
list-style-position     Yes              No         Iside or outside.
list-style-image        Yes              No         Custom bullet image for the whole list.
margin                  Yes              Yes        On UL: spacing from other elements; on LI: spacing between items.
padding                 Yes              Yes        Similar to margin, context matters.
width / max-width       Yes              Yes        Usually UL for container width, LI for item width.
height                  No               Yes        UL height auto; LI can have fixed height per item.
background-color        Yes              Yes        UL for full container background, LI for per-item background.
border                  Yes              Yes        UL for container border, LI for item borders.
display: flex / grid    Yes              No         UL becomes layout container for children.
text-align              No               Yes        Align content inside each LI.
overflow / white-space  Yes              No         Usually applies to container to manage child clipping.
float / clear           Yes              Yes        UL to float the whole list; LI to float items individually.
font / color            No               Yes        Usually per-item styling.

